1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:03,001
In this tutorial, you'll learn about accessibility, what it is, why it's important, and how accessible sites benefit everyone.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:12,000
What is accessibility?

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:14,000
First, the what.

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:16,000
As a subset of digital accessibility, web accessibility means building sites that all people, regardless of their abilities, can use.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:25,000
In the most general straightforward sense, accessibility guarantees universal and equal access to content and services.

6
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:32,000
As you learn or practice accessibility, you'll encounter technical terms.

7
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Let's clarify them.

8
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:38,000
A11Y is a numerical abbreviation of the word accessibility, where 11 represents the number of letters between A and Y.

9
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
WCAG or WCAG is short for web content accessibility guidelines, an international accessibility standard developed through the World Wide Web Consortium.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,000
The foundational principles of WCAG or WCAG are dubbed "POUR", "P-O-U-R", "Perceivable", "Oprable", "Understandable" and "Robust".

11
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Let's start with "Perceivable".

12
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:10,000
"Perceivable" means delivering the information so that anyone can understand it.

13
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
For example, provide text alternatives for audio-visual content like images or videos.

14
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Secondly, "Oprable".

15
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:29,000
"Oprable" refers to enabling people to use the interface and interact with the site.

16
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,000
For example, support keyboard functionality instead of mouse-only interactions.

17
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,000
Thirdly, "Understandable" ensures people can comprehend the information and use interfaces.

18
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Lastly, "Robust".

19
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Robust means content remains accessible as technology advances and evolves.

20
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
For example, use correct markup to guarantee compatibility with current and future browsers and assistive technologies.

21
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,000
Next, let's talk about some misconceptions.

22
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
All this sounds reasonable enough.

23
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,000
Yet, businesses and web makers are reluctant, citing common misconceptions.

24
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Some of the misconceptions might be that people say accessibility is hard.

25
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Yes, so is coding, writing and even baking souffles.

26
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Still, humanity has managed to accomplish these tasks for decades, even centuries.

27
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Secondly, some people might say accessible websites are poorly designed.

28
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
This is simply not true.

29
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:36,000
An accessible website would be as beautiful as your skills and project requirements allow it to be.

30
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Thirdly, some might state compliance is expensive.

31
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:46,000
Yes, that is sometimes true.

32
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,000
That's why one should create an inclusive experience from the get-go.

33
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Treating it as an afterthought, something you could solve with an add-on just before launch, is always the less sensible costly approach.

34
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,000
Lastly, some would argue accessibility is a nice to have.

35
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:06,000
On the contrary, it's as instrumental to a site as the client's branding, the team's coding standards or your language's grammar rules.

36
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:15,000
You won't deliberately introduce bugs, so why would you make things inaccessible?

37
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
A better way to think about accessibility is as a code name for empathy.

38
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:26,000
That makes it much harder to ignore and intuitive to adopt.

39
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:30,000
More than the legal compliance, commercial liability and financial implications, it's about fundamental human rights.

40
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,000
In 2006, the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities defined access to information and communications technologies as a basic human right.

41
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,000
According to the W3C's 2018 report, there were over 1 billion people with disabilities worldwide.

42
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:57,000
And WebAIM's latest report found that 95.9% of the top million home pages had accessibility issues.

43
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
96.4% of the errors detected fall into six categories, namely low contrast text, missing form input label, empty buttons, no alternative text for images, empty links and no document language.

44
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
These six issues have plagued the web for 25 years since WCAG 1.0 was released in 1999.

45
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Next, why is accessibility important? Accessibility isn't only a legal requirement in many countries. It's good for business too.

46
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
People with disabilities have a massive spending power, yet the overwhelming majority of websites neglect to take them into account.

47
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:50,000
The following demonstrations help illustrate some difficulties many of them have to overcome.

48
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,000
In the first example, we will see how a non-visually impaired user would see the page in optimal conditions.

49
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
The design includes non-default styling, small fonts, links without underlines and insufficient color contrast.

50
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Now, if this is not easy to navigate for a non-visually impaired person, how much more difficult will it be for someone who is visually impaired?

51
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
The next two examples emulate how users with vision deficiencies would see the page.

52
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
In the first example, we will see the impact of low contrast, small fonts and no underline on links.

53
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
In the second example, we will see that sometimes a screen might be a complete blur.

54
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
In the next example, I added an accordion to a post and then interacted with it using the mouse.

55
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:44,000
I then disabled JavaScript in the browser and tried to interact with it.

56
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:48,000
As the video demonstrates, it's impossible to use without JavaScript.

57
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:53,000
In the last example, I simulated a user navigating through the page with a keyboard, using the tab key to move forward and shift plus tab keys to move backward.

58
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:03,000
The links, the search form and the YouTube video are properly marked when focused, but they yes/no buttons or not.

59
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
When developers or designers alter the default styling of interactive elements, in this case the buttons, to hide the visual indication of the focused element, the user can't tell if they are active.

60
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:23,000
The takeaway is that accessible sites aren't a bonus. They are essential for so many of us.

61
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:29,000
The range of disabilities is as diverse as humanity, covering everything from physical to cognitive to mental.

62
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:37,000
Permanent blindness to age related vision impairment.

63
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
Temporary hearing loss to difficulty concentrating.

64
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Broken wrist to epilepsy; dyslexia to ADHD.

65
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Color blindness to multiple sclerosis.

66
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:55,000
And the list can go on.

67
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:57,000
That's a multitude of people who are unable to fill out forms, navigate through sites, recognize links in texts, discern images, consume podcasts and videos or add items to the cart.

68
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:11,000
In conclusion, accessibility, even on the web alone, is a broad multifaceted topic that's impossible to cover in a few minutes.

69
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:20,000
We encourage you to learn more. Read, experiment and advocate for change.

70
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:26,000
Since over a third of the web's most visited site use WordPress, our community is pivotal in making the web more accessible.

71
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:34,000
You don't need to be a certified accessibility expert. Anyone involved in online creation can make a difference.

